John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective endeavors.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for later higher education, their chosen career and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of developing and adopting a personalized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages continue to be a popular and in demand subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his native language, the message will reach the heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exams, we can observe that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of pupils who studied foreign languages got top marks.
The data, collected by the 74 member schools of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students got the highest grade with honors in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish got the highest grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as core skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technique and mathematics) in the study plans of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons employees indicated for the difficulty in filling jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
For this reason language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring knowledge of languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you are learning a second language, you will have an actual advantage in the future with a lifetime competence like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically lead a multilingual person to the front of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language teaching is so important for today's children.
Knowledge of multiple languages, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a viable job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK by looking to 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be several languages to choose from in independent schools, with the teaching staff specializing in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary for success, whatever their future.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the country's future, and this must be reflected in teaching.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
The faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
