"However, we do not see any compliant response from the US," he said.
"Without trust in the US there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
Although Ri re-used the well-known complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization in full as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever meeting between an incumbent U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised North Korean security guarantees.
North Korea sought a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed appeals to ease the strict international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The US insists on the need to 'have denuclearization first' and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose coercively and even oppose the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust."
Ri did not refer to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader had announced at the UN earlier this week.
The minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past 5 months and added: "If the counterpart to this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be dead at this point."
But even so, the tone of Ri's speech was noticeably different from last year's speech to the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with North Korea's missiles after "the president of evil" Trump had called Kim a "missile man" engaged in a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, poured praise on Kim for his courage in embarking on the path of disarmament, but stated that much still needs to be done and that the sanctions will remain in place until North Korea is denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no deadline, stating that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
Cine and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for actions taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo stated Thursday to the UN Security Council that: "Respect for the Security Council sanctions must continue forcefully and without exception until complete, final and proven denuclearization is achieved."
The Security Council unanimously supported sanctions against North Korea in 2006 in an effort to stifle funding for nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
