Harvard students take a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has prompted all of its students to sleep more in an effort to counter the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights fed by caffeine.
One university scholar has found that students at the world's number one university often have no idea of the basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes to be the first of its kind in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after a lecture he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, âWhy am I only being told this now, when I am in my senior year?'
She said that no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first given this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course involves a number of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dormitory room, where students can select cups of coffee, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "night off to study" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to lack of sleep being a growing problem.
Sleep enough and with good quality sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and even should serve to avoid fattening since lack of sleep brings the brain into starvation mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar study program before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm clock for when they need to go to bed, as well as for when they need to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleep problems.
