Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt "inferior" because of sexuality
Olympic swimmer Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to anyone because of his sexuality - but this gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he did not realize, until he got to secondary school, that "not everyone is like me."
Speaking on the first episode of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he had made his voice heard about gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also stated that being a parent meant that he cared less about winning the Olympics.
The usual presenter of the longtime program, Kirsty Young, took a series of months off due to illness.
Presenting himself as an outcast in Laverne's first program, Daley said he felt "less than" anyone else as he grew up because "it wasn't socially acceptable that he liked both boys and girls."
He said, "Nowadays, the feeling of feeling less than, and feeling different, was the things that really gave me the strength and energy to succeed."
He wanted to prove that he was "something," he said, so he wouldn't let anyone down if they happened to find out about his sexuality.
The two-time bronze medalist at the Olympics has become a high-profile LGBT activist and used his face in this year's Australian Commonwealth Games to appeal to multiple countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he made his voice heard because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without consequences and wanted to give "hope" to others.
The three-time world champion said that falling in love with a man - American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013- "took me by surprise".
Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, last year, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When you pass so many at a young age" - he went to his first Olympics when he was 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was hard to find someone the same age who had experienced similar ups and downs.
The two became parents in June, of a child named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said his "whole perspective" has changed.
"If you asked me last year, it was all about the fact that 'I had to win a gold medal,'" he said.
"You know what, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medalist is Robbie."
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said that his father had not accepted the fact that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets for London 2012 - because he wanted to be in the front row.
"I couldn't tell him 'you're not going to be around here so you can be in the front row, Dad,'" he said.
"I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and until he actually stopped and died, I hadn't yet realized he wasn't invincible," he said.
The following year Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics, winning bronze.
"I just knew that was what I had dreamed of all my life - swimming in front of a home audience in the Olympic Games, there was no better feeling," he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song - Heather Small's Proud - which had a particular significance to him in preparing for the Olympics and still gives him goose bumps.
