The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research at an estate in the Scottish Highlands aims to reveal how bats use their eyesight to obtain food.
It is confided that the discoveries can shed light on the behavior of the only existing flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and soprano, as well as brown mumps and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens, Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
Analysis of recorded sounds by an expert will determine the frequency of calls of bats and the way each species behaves.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed scaled-up picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of lawns, and how to best maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The bat population in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work affecting trespoli and ruining habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to domestic cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their night-hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to grabbing a prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-location technique to detect insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for taking care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the trespoles, and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organisation has even established Scotland's first bat reserve at the Threave estate, in the Dumfries and Galloway region, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The head of the estate, David Thompson, states that ownership is the ideal territory.
"Here in Threave we have a large area for bats," he said.
"We have the ancient buildings, many centuries-old trees and a good habitat.
But there's a lot about bats that we don't know yet, so the work we do here and in the other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs."
It stresses the importance of controlling bats before conducting maintenance within the properties as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternal trestle could kill up to 400 females and young, perhaps wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their trespoles.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He stated, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don't know how their populations fare."
