Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission's latest report shows a general decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom extends about 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas County south of Lee County.
The patches are about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a low to high concentration off Hillsborough County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, a background concentration to an average concentration in Charlotte County, a background concentration to a high concentration in the Lee County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
While no cases were reported in northwest Florida last week.
